[Student "S"]
{South is to play 3NT. West leads the \SK.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=2  \D=0  \C=2  Total = 5

Even if \Hs split 3-3 you could only get 2 extra winners there, so it should be clear that you must establish the \Ds. You will have to drive out the \DA and hope they don't win too many \Ss at that time. You can help your chances by a hold-up of the \SA until the third round.

Having just taken the third \S trick you now work on \Ds by first playing the \DK, then continuing the suit. East wins the third one with his \DA. And now the good news - he has no \S left to reach his partner's good tricks. So East plays the \HQ.

At this point in the play you have three tricks in the bank; \SA, \DK, \DQ. You take your \HK, cash the two good \Ds, then lead to dummy for the \CA K and \HA. Voila!  

You were lucky that East had the \DA since he only had 3 \Ss.

But what if East actually held 4 \Ss? No problem, in that case the \Ss would have split 4-4 so the defenders could only win 3 \S tricks and the \DA.

The hold-up lets you make the contract whenever East holds the \DA. And if West happened to hold the \DA??? You go down.}
[Play "W"]SK

